[center][b][size=15pt][anchor=part1]Simple GUI[/anchor][/size][/b][/center]

here is what we will be making today.
[img]http://img253.imageshack.us/img253/3393/guiej6.png[/img]

I will show you how to add simple buttons and simple actions for the buttons.

what you will need first is eclipse, its what i use but i guess anythings fine. you can get eclipse from here - http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/  download the SDK.

when you open eclipse you will see the following - 
[img]http://img296.imageshack.us/img296/8428/eclipsedx7.png[/img]

to run a program go to run > run as > java application

now, go to file, new, project.

when the window comes up click java project in the tree below the first text field.

then in the column to the right you will see your project.now go to file, new, class.

when it comes up set the following to the following:

package: JavaAIO

Name:GUI

and select public static void main string.

now in the middle of eclipse its like notepad. paste this in there

[code]

package JavaAIO;


import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
import java.io.*;

public class GUI extends JFrame 
{
	public static void main(String[] args) 
	{
		new GUI();		
	}

	public GUI() 
	{
        }

}
[/code]

[b][i]Please note: If you do not have or dont want to download eclipse, then just remove 'package JavaAIO'[/i][/b]


[code]
import javax.swing.*;
[/code]
is importing swing, wich is GUI.

[code]
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
[/code]

is importing the layout type, for this tut we will be using flow.

now we will add a window to the GUI.

make public GUI() look like this:
[code]
public GUI() 
	{
		this.setSize(330,200);
		this.setResizable(false);
		   this.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			this.setTitle("GUI");

}
[/code]

now the setsize is self explanatory, sets the size of the window.
if you set it resizable as true you can maximize and minimize your program.
and this.setTile sets the title of your program.

dont try to run it now because we need to add more code, but if you wish to run it, add a 
[code]
this.setVisible(true);
[/code]
to the bottom of your code.

now to add a button.

to add a button you need a panel to add it on, to create a panel add this:
[code]
JPanel panel1 = new JPanel();[/code]
 after the
[code]
this.setTitle("GUI");
[/code]

so it looks like this:
[code]
public GUI() 
	{
		this.setSize(330,200);
		this.setResizable(false);
		   this.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			this.setTitle("GUI");			

			JPanel panel1 = new JPanel();
}
[/code]
 then to add a button add this right after the JPanel line
[code]
JButton button1 = new JButton("Button");[/code]

so it looks like this.
[code]
public GUI() 
	{
		this.setSize(330,200);
		this.setResizable(false);
		   this.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			this.setTitle("GUI");			

			JPanel panel1 = new JPanel();
			JButton button1 = new JButton("Button");
[/code]
what you have done is added a button under the name "button1". the text in the (" "); at the end of the button line is what the text will be on the button, so mine is simply 'button'.
now to add the panel,
press enter after the button1 line and put this:
[code]
this.add(panel1);
[/code]
now to add those buttons to the panel. add this after the line you just added:
[code]
panel1.add(button1);
[/code]
that tells the panel to add your button.
now after that you can add this:
[code]
this.setVisible(true);
[/code]

then your whole code should look like this:
[code]
//If you are using notepad or a different program remove package JavaAIO;
package JavaAIO;

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
import java.io.*;

public class GUI extends JFrame 
{
	public static void main(String[] args) 
	{
		new GUI();		
	}

	public GUI() 
	{
		this.setSize(330,200);
		this.setResizable(false);
		   this.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			this.setTitle("GUI");			

			JPanel panel1 = new JPanel();
			JButton button1 = new JButton("Button");
			this.add(panel1);
			panel1.setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.CENTER));
			panel1.add(button1);
			this.setVisible(true);


	}

}
[/code]

congratulations, you have made your first gui!




[u]
[b]other:[/b]
[/u]

adding a label,
[code]
JLabel label1 = new JLabel("text here");
[/code]
a lable is txt.
then add the label by typing this Before or after 'panel1.add(button1);' depending on were you want it
[code]
panel1.add(label1);
[/code]



[center]
[b][size=15pt][anchor=part2]Adding action to your button[/anchor][/size][/b][/center]

this one wont be as long, we will be continuing from the other code we just used.

make your:
[code]
 public class GUI extends JFrame 
[/code]
look like this
[code]
public class GUI extends JFrame implements ActionListener
[/code]
This adds ActionListener to be recognized in your class.
After that, add these imports:
[code]
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;
[/code]

Now look for these brackets at the end of 'public void GUI()'
[code]
    }

}
[/code]

After that, add this following method. This method will allow a button component (like 'button1' 'button2' etc.) To have an action.
[code]
public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent evt) {
        String cmd = evt.getActionCommand();
        if(cmd.equals("BUTTON NAME")) {
       	 try {
       		 //what the button does (will be explained)
       		} catch (Exception e) {}
        }       		

}
[/code]

Where it says 'BUTTON NAME' add the component name of your button. So for example, if the button you want to add action to looks like:
<blockquote>JButton [b]button1[/b] = new JButton("Click me!");</blockquote>
You would take the name that is in bold above.

This is what it would look like after you do that:
<blockquote>public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent evt) {
        String cmd = evt.getActionCommand();
        if(cmd.equals("[b]button1[/b]")) {
       	 try {
       		 //what the button does (will be explained)
       		} catch (Exception e) {}
        }       		

}</blockquote>
Once you have done that, take your component (button1) or whatever it was, and add this:
[code]
button1.addActionListener(this);
[/code]

Place that line after
[code]
panel1.add(button1);
[/code]

[center]
[b][size=15pt][anchor=part3]Actions for your buttons.[/anchor][/size][/b][/center]

[b]Open Webpage[/b]

To open a webpage, delet the line '//what the button does' and add the following:
[code]
Runtime.getRuntime().exec("rundll32 url.dll,FileProtocolHandler http://www.URL.com");
[/code]
Where it says 'www.URL.com' is where you put the website, so delete URL and type the name.


[b]Close The Program[/b]

This is to close the program, like a 'cancel' button, just delete the line that has // and add this:
[code]
System.exit(0);
[/code]

[b]Making a button open another JFrame[/b]

This will make it so when you click a button, it will open another JFrame.

Hopefully you already understand the 'delete the // line' concept, so ill just jump to the case.
Earlier in the tutorial, when you declared the first JFrame, you will be doing the same thing, but treating the
action method as if its the GUI method. So it would like this:
[code]
public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent evt) {
        String cmd = evt.getActionCommand();
        if(cmd.equals("[b]button1[/b]")) {
       	 try {
         JFrame frame2 = new JFrame();
           frame2.setSize(330,200);
		frame2.setResizable(false);
		   frame2.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			frame2.setTitle("GUI 2");	
                        } catch (Exception e) {}
              }       		

 }	
[/code]

Once you have done that, make sure on your new jframes you replace 'this' with the jframe name.


Once you are done the full code should look somewhat close to the following:
[code]
//If you are using notepad or a different program remove package JavaAIO;
package JavaAIO;

import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
import java.io.*;

public class GUI extends JFrame 
{
	public static void main(String[] args) 
	{
		new GUI();		
	}

	public GUI() 
	{
		this.setSize(330,200);
		this.setResizable(false);
		   this.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			this.setTitle("GUI");			

			JPanel panel1 = new JPanel();
			JButton button1 = new JButton("Button");
			this.add(panel1);
			panel1.setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.CENTER));
			panel1.add(button1);
			this.setVisible(true);


	}

}



public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent evt) {
        String cmd = evt.getActionCommand();
        if(cmd.equals("[b]button1[/b]")) {
       	 try {
         JFrame frame2 = new JFrame();
           frame2.setSize(330,200);
		frame2.setResizable(false);
		   frame2.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);	   
			frame2.setTitle("GUI 2");	
                        } catch (Exception e) {}
              }       		

 }	
[/code]

Happy coding :)


